            <div type="translation">
                <p>The people of <placeName ref="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/599810">Mylasa</placeName>, the people of <placeName ref="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/599479">Alabanda</placeName>, [the people of -, the people of-]
                    (honor) Lanthes, son of Prodikos, for judging.</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription is an honorary stele dedicated to a man named Lanthes, son of
                    Prodikos, possibly from Assos, as this is where the stele was found. While no
                    other information about him exists, it is safe to assume he was of high social
                    rank which allowed him to serve as a judge. The context in which he served as
                    judge is uncertain: he might have been a judge in an athletic competition or
                    some form of arbitration. The stele can be dated to 1st century BCE based on
                    paleography: the serifs used came into use in the 3rds century BCE, broken-bar
                    alpha was in use between the 3rd and 1st centuries BCE, and the full π started
                    replacing the partial π in the 1st century BCE. </p></div>
            

